{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_lethifold_ver01/data/sn86086067/00414214708/1908032501/0563.xml":{"full_text":"CORN PRF .iNNERS.\nResult o .e Contest Held at North\nFreedom.\nThe following are the winners in the\ncorn contest at North Freedom. The\nreport should have appeared before but\nthe one having the second was called\naway and it has been impossible to ob\ntain the result for the publication until\nnow.\nYellow Dent \u2014Toole\u2019s North Star.\n1 Lawrence Wilcox, Dist No. 7,\nFairfield.\n2 Leo Crawley, Dist. No. 11, Bam\nboo.\n3 Walter Liegel, Dist. No. 2, Frank\nlin.\n4 Paul Puttkammer, Dist. No. 7,\nFairfield.\n5 Grant Burton, Dist. No. 7, Fair\nfield.\n(i Orrin Burton, Dist. No. 7, Fair\nfield.\n7 James Dickie, Dist. Jt. 1 5 North\nFreedom.\nWhit Dent\u2014 Wisconsin No 7.\n1 Raymond Sherwood, Dist. No. 5,\nSpring Green.\n2 John Hemberger, Dist. Jt. 10,\nFranklin.\n3 Floyd Hemberger, Dist. Jt. 10,\nFranklin.\n4 Willie Schroeder,Dist.No.2, Wood\nland.\nProf. R. A. Moore of Madison acted\nas judge. The business men of the\nvillage contributed liberal prizes to en\ncourage the boys in their first corn\ngrowing contest.\nIn addition to the two pure bred\nvarieties of com grown the past years,\nsoy beans and Oderbrucker barley\nwill be grown in the contest next sea\nson. Seed may be procured from the\ncount of superintendent,\nG. W. DAVIES,\nNorth Freedom.\nBACK TO THE UNITED STATES.\nH\nMr. and Mrs. Guy O. Glazier Leave\nPuetro Cortez.\nMr. and Mrs. Guy O. Glazier have\nchanged their location from Puerto\nCortez, Honduras, Central America,\nwhere they have resided for the past\nfourteen months, according to a letter\nreceived at this office. Mr. Glazier\nwrites that Mr. and Mrs. C. W. Eggles.\nton are still in Honduras but expect to\nreturn in J une. The Glazier and Eggles\nton families formerly resided in Sauk\ncounty and Kilbourn. Their many\nfriends will be glad to receive this\nmessage after their long silence.\nSAD DEATH OF A YOUNG MAN.\nComes to His Home in Sauk County\nand Soon Passes Away.\nArthur Du\u00dfois, son of Mr. and Mrs.\nWilliam Du\u00dfois, who died at the\nhome of his parents in Winfield\nnot far from lteedsburg Wednesday\nnight of dyptheria was well known in\nBaraboo. The young man arrivd home\nfrom Mineral Point in the afternoon\napparently in good health. He was\ntaken sick in the evening and died\nshortly afterward. The remains were\nlaid to rest in Butterfield cemetery\nThursday. He was a relative of\nMrs. S. A. Faber, 323 Martin street,\nand was formerly employed by A. S.\nHawley.\nDeceased w r as born in the town of\nExcelsior, Nov. 12, 1881, and died\nMarch 19, 1908. For the past two years\nhe had oeen at Mineral Point in the\ncement block business.\nBesides his parents he leaves tw o\nbrothers, Charles of Narrow\u2019s and\nForest of North Freedom.\nELKS ELECTION.\nThe Elks have elected the following\nof icers for the ensuing term:\nE. R.\u2014W. J. Power.\nE. Leading Kt.\u2014Win. H. Pahl.\nE. Lodge Kt.\u2014E. W. Van Aiken.\nE. Lect. Kt.\u2014H. Okern.\nSec\u2019y.\u2014E. G. Marriott.\nTreas.\u2014T. W. English.\nEsq.\u2014Dr. Roger Cahoon.\nTrustee\u2014B. G. Gollmar.\nRepresentative to Grand Lodge,\nDallas, Texas.\u2014W. J. Power.\nGot on the Water Wagon.\nThe report comes from Merrimack\nthat the saloon in the town of Merri\nmack has been closed on account of\npoor patronage. Since the voters have\nplaced the little village on the \u201cdry\ndock,\u201d a saloon has been conducted in\nthe town of Merrimack, by Pearl\nThompson, just outside the village\nlimits, and for a time did a land office\nbusiness. On New Year\u2019s Day it is\nsaid, many of its best customers turned\nover anew leaf and since have clung\nto the \u201cwaterw r agon,\u201dthus putting the\nsaloon out of business.\u2014Prairie du Sac\nNews.\nANOTHER DEUV\n11 m use\nI\nIn the Dizzy case an abatement has\nbeen filed by the attorney for the city\ncouncil, asking that the former or\noriginal action should be dismissed\nand the costs assessed before proceed\ning further on the ground that there is\nalready an action before the court. The\nplaintiff looks upon the abatement as\ntaking an exception to the judge\u2019s de\ncision.\nAs to whether or not he will hear\nthe arguments on the abatement is not\nknown.\nSEVERELY BITTED BY A HOG.\nGilbert Voeck of North Freedom Ser\niously Injured by a Savage Ani\nmal.\nOn Sunday Gilbert Voeck, aged 13,\nwas severely bitten by a savage hog on\nSunday. The boy was severely injured\nat one of his knees. It is thought that\nthe hog was bitten by a dog and for\nthis reason hydrophobia is feared.\nThe hog and dog will be watched for\nsome days to see what may develop.\nGilbert is the son of John Voeck who\nwas formerly foreman of the section at\nNorth Freedom and who recently sold\nhis farm to the mining company for a\nchoice sum.\nFOUR GENERATIONS CELEBRATE.\nHold a Reunion at the Home of Mr.\nand Mrs. L. E. Reynolds.\nOn Sunday there was a family\ngathering at the home of Mr. and\nMrs. L. E. Reynolds north-west of the\ncity.\nArthur and Ethan Reynolds an\ntheir families of the town 'of Delton\nwere present and also Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge Reynolds and son of Benton,\nWis. The oldest in the group of four\ngenerations is Mrs. Mary Ann Her\nrick mother of Mrs. L. E. Reynolds\nand the others are successively Mrs.L.\nE. Reynolds and her son, George, and\nhis son Glen.\nMr. Reynolds reports that every\nthing is very quiet in the lead region\nbut that with a return of prosperity\nactivities will be renewed.\nDIED IN NEW MEXICO.\nSad Demise of Robert Bittrich Who\nWent from Home for His Health.\n(From Saturday's Daily.)\nRelatives of Robert Bittrich received\na message today stating that he died\nlast night at East Las Vegas, New\nMexico, to which place lie went some\ndays ago for his health.He was troubled\nwith hemorrhage in connection w r ith\nconsumption and it is supposed that a\nsudden attack caused his demise. He\nwas aged 29 and has alw r ays resided\nnear Baraboo. His brother,Otto, went\nwith him and will return with the re\nmains.\n(From Monday\u2019s Dally.)\nSince Saturday friends have received\na letter from East Las Vegas, New\nMexico, which stated that Robert\nBittrich collapsed while walking on\nthe street with his cousin, Otto. Only\na few days before he had written to his\nwife that he felt ever so much better\nand believed that he would entirely\nrecover. She expected to leave for\nLas Vegas soon in order to be with\nhim.\nGOOD LECTORE GIVEN.\nMeeting Held Under Auspices ot the\nMen\u2019s League.\nThe illustrated lecture at the Con\ngregational church last evening by W.\nJ. Warner was interesting and educa\ntional. The unique feature was the\nillustrations which were copies of the\nfamous cartoons of the Ram\u2019s Horn.\nThe speaker gave many interesting\nstatistics concerning saloons and the\nresults of their existence. He said that\nthere were more than 600 towns in\nWisconsin which are \u201cdry\u201d. Over\n$1,000,000,000 is spent yearly by patrons\nof the saloons, he mentioned. The\npictures were sermons in themselves\nand were not confined entirely to the\nliquor question. Every folly of human\nnature was exhibited in a remarkably\nforcible manner. Most of the seats in\nthe church were taken and the\naudience showed themselves well\npleased with the lecturer and his views.\nThe speaker was secured by the Men\u2019s\nLeague of the Congregational church.\nMAY LIVE A CENTURY.\nRev. John B. Dearholt of Reedsburg\nAged 97 on Sunday.\nThe Rev. Jno. B. Dearholt of Reeds\nburg, Wisconsin, celebrated his ninety\nseventh birthday on Sunday the\ntwenty second of this month, having\nbeen bom in 1811 at Baltimore, Md.\nIn early manhood he went to Morough\ncounty, Ohio, where he was married.\nDuring his residence in Ohio he was\npastor of a church of the Christian de\nnomination. Of his six children but\ntwo are living at the present time,\nSylvester and Temperance. In 1855\nREV. JOHJN B. DEARHOLT,\nof aged 97.\nhe removed to Wisconsin with his\nfamily and organized a pioneer Christ\nian church in Sauk county, town of\nIronton. This he watched over and\nministered to as long as his health and\nage permitted.\nAbout three years after the death of\nhis wife in 1871, he was again married\nand has two living adult children from\nthis marriage, Lulu and Irvin.\nBom before the development of the\nrailroad, steamship, telegraph and\ntelephone-, his life has been touched by\ntransformations which have become\nfirmly established in history and in\nfact. Asa small boy of three, perched\nupon his father\u2019s shoulder, he wit\nnessed the mustering out of the soldiers\nof the war of 1812-14. So little respect\nhas the youthful mind for the proper\nrelation of events however, that he\nconfesses that his most vivid recollect\nion of the day was a little new red cap\nthat he wore.\nAn interesting episode in his migra\ntion from Ohio to Wisconsin, was an\noffer he rejected of a blacksmith shop\nand real estate in what is now the\nbusiness center of Chicago, in exchange\nfor a team of horses. Chicago at that\ntime was but an unpromising munici\npality.\nThe life of a pioneer pastor in those\ntimes, was no sinecure, and involved\nbeside the ordinary duties of a pastor\nate, usually the bulk of the support\nand maintenance of the church, not to\nmention the physical as well as sp rit\nual comforting of the sick and needy.\nWhile dramatic material changes\nhave occurred in this world of ours\nduring the last century, no less start\nling changes have been wrought in\neducational and religious thought. It\nhas been a matter of pride aud wonder\nment to his friends, the manner in\nwhich Mr. Dearholt has accommo\ndated himself to these new habits of\nthought and belief. Out of an age of\nalmost fanatic fervor and intolerance,\nhe has kept in complete accord with\nthe newer developments of a religion\nof charity and love.\nWithal, he has never lost the simple\nfaith that \u201cthe Lord will provide\u201d\nand his life therefore has been blessed\nwith a peace and quiet that have been\ndenied the average disciple of the pres\nent commercial and industrial age.\nHe is now fighting an ambitious\nand apparently winning battle to live\nout his century.\nThe following are the names and ad\ndresses of the children:\n8. J. Dearholt, Milwaukee, Wis.\nLee A. Dearholt, Milwaukee, Wis.\nDr. N. E. Dearholt, Milwaukee, Wis.\nJohn B. Dearholt, Reedsburg, Wis.\nJohn W. Dearholt, Loganville, Wis.\nMrs. Eliza Wheeler, Limeridge,\nWis.\nMrs. Flora Alexander, Ironw r ood,\nMich.\nGeorge DeKoeyer,carrier of R. F. D.\nNo. 5, will quit the Route on March 31\nand in a few 7 days will leave with A.\nH. Pratt of New York for a trip to\nGrand Junction, Colorado. Mr. De\nKoeyer takes a leave of absence of six\nmonths. His place will be taken by\nBert Gollmar and DeKoeyer suggests\nthat all of the patrons on the route\nplace their names on the boxes as an\naid to the new worker for Uncle Sam\nCASTOR IA\nFor Infants and Children*\nThe Kind You Have Always Bougtit\nBears the /ny\nSignature of\nLARGE REPUBLICAN\nMEETING HELD\nADDRESSES BY DUCAN MCGRE\nGOR OF PLATTVILLE AND ATJ\u2019Y\nMCGOVERN OF MILWAUKEE.\nTHE CLUB ELECTS OFFICERS\nSeveral Present from Reedsburg to\nListen to the Speeches\u2014J. L.\nBonham Presides.\nAt the A. O. U. W. hall on Friday\nnight there was a rousing Republican\nmeeting with splendid speeches and\nan election of officers in the club. James\nL. Bonham presided and the following\nwell known and substantial citizens\nwere selected as officers of the organiza\ntion:\nPresident\u2014Carl Isenberg.\nSecretary\u2014Elmer Johnston.\nTreasurer\u2014John E. Witwen.\nExecutive committee\u2014 J. B. Don\novan, A. G. Buckley and F. E. Sliults.\nProfessor Duncan McGregor, assem\nblyman from Grant county,first spoke\nand told of the work of Senator La\nFollette in the state along the line of\nthe rate commission, civil service bill,\nequal taxation and other reforms. He\nalso spoke of his work in the senate.\nMr. McGregor is one of the delegates\nselected to the national republican con\nvention and pledged himself first, last\nand all the time to support Senator La\nFollette for president in the conven\ntion.\nDistrict Attorney Francis E. McGov\nern of Milwaukee, also addressed the\nmeeting and among other things said:\nLa Follette, Mr. McGovern said, has\nshown Wisconsin the way to grapple\nwith the foes of government. His rec\nord in Wisconsin showed that his\nbrain is large enough in his purpose,in\ndependent enough in character and ex\nperienced enough in public affairs to\ninsure the carrying forward of a com\nplete programme of these policies. Mr.\nMcGovern said that the way Senator\nLa Follette had done things was quite\nas significant as were the things he\nhid done.\nA number were present from out of\ntown among them being W.W. Powell\nof the Milwaukee Free Press; Clarence\nPowell, Ora Cottington, Grant Dryer\nand Henry Hines of Reedsburg.\nA large number signed to become\nmembers of the club.\nResolutions Adopted\nThe following resolutions were\nadopted.\nWhereas we as Republicans of Wis\nconsin have watched with pride and\nappreciation the useful career of Sena\ntor Robert M. La Follette, both as\ngovernor of this state and as a member\nof the United States, and\nWhereas we admire the stand he has\ntaken and unqualifiedly approve his\nefforts to restore the reins of govern\nment to the hands of the people and\nWhereas we have an abiding confi\ndence in his ability, his integrity, his\ncourage and his thoroughness, and\nWhereas we believe that the econo\nmic and industrial conditions now con\nfronting the American people call for\neffective regulation and control of all\npublic service corporations and that\nthe times demand courageous and able\nleadership, now therefore be it\nResolved that we hereby recommend\nto the Republicans of the nation the\nconsideration of Senator LaFollette\nas a man whose record of reforms writ\nten into effective, laws in this state\nmarks him as one especially equipped\nand qualified to lead the national\nmovement for the restoration of repre\nsentative government, and one, whose\nability, fearlessness and steadfastness\nhaving been tried in the fire of experi\nence, who is particularly available as a\nsuccessor to President Roosevelt. Be\nit further\nResolved that this organization is\nperfected for the purpose of furthering\nthe candidacy of Senator La Follette\nfor the Republican nomination for\npresident and that we pledge ourselves\nto use every honorable means to secure\nhis nomination by the Republican\nnational convention at Chicago in\nJune, 1908.\nOBITUARY\n(From Saturday'* Dally.)\nThe funeral of Mrs. Gustav Zick of\nLeland, who died suddenly of heart\nfailure this week, will be held tomor\nrow at 10 o\u2019clock in the forenoon at\nLeland.\nDeceased was 53 years of age and\nleaves a husband, one daughter, Miss\nEmma,two sons, William and Hermam\nof Leland; three sisters, Mrs. Louis\nHarthaus, Mrs. Frank Jaquish, and\nMrs. Matt Hamberger, of Baraboo;\nand three brothers, William, Albert,\nand August Redel of Baraboo. Mrs.\nJohn Leiser of this city is a niece of\nthe deceased.\nBADGERS HOLD REUNION.\nEnjoy a Day on the Coast of Flori\nda.\nRecently a large number of people\nfrom Wisconsin gathered at the Gulf\nCasino, in Florida, where a reunion\nwas held. Among the numbers on the\nprogram was a poem by Dr. Martin of\nMerrimack, in this county. Here is\nthe poem:\nFlorida Farewell.\n(By M. T. Martin, M. D.,\nof Merrimack, Wis.)\nEach tourist\u2019s heart will always jump\nWith strenuous and tumultuous\nthump,\nAnd all liis being glow aflame\nWhene\u2019er he hears his home-state\u2019s\nname.\nThe East will boast against the West,\nThe North against the South contest,\nAnd strive by every shrewd device\nTo prove their state a paradise.\nBut, when it comes to our rare State,\nSo grand, so marvelously great;\nUpon a pinnacle so high,\nIts point doth pierce the deep blue sky.\nAll other States forget their pride,\nTheir exultations all subside,\nWhen they behold, in beauty bright,\nWisconsin\u2019s majesty and might*\nThe greatest lakes since Time began,\nSuperior and Michigan;\nIn summer\u2019s songs and winter\u2019s roars\nRoll ever on her rocky shores.\nOld Mississippi\u2019s solemn stream,\nIn noontide sun and moonlight gleam,\nHas swept in splendor\u2019s stately tide,\nSix thousand years her western side.\nWisconsin, if she really tries,\nIs sure to carry off the prize,\nIn farms, all others she outshines;\nShe has the biggest iron mines.\nShe has the highest banks of snow,\nAll other winds she can out-blow;\nShe makes the very thickest ice,\nAnd freezes noses white and nice.\nWisconsin thus our love impels,\nWe love her hills and mossy dells;\nWe love her prairies, rocks and herds;\nWe love her flowers, bees and birds.\nWe love the Southland just as well,\nAnd long in this fair realm to dwell;\nWe love our southern friends so true,\nAnd Lath are we to say, Adieu.\nAnd yet, the day is drawing nigh,\nTo say to these kind friends, good-by;\nAnd some, perhaps, have grown so dear\nThe parting words may call a tear.\nWe soon must leave this land of shine,\nWe soon must leave the peerless pine,\nThe meek palmetto and the palm,\nThe land of gladness and of calm.\nWe\u2019ll miss old ocean\u2019s restless tide,\nWhere pelicans so jiroudly ride;\nWe\u2019ll miss the buzzards, soaring free;\nWe\u2019ll miss the festive little flea.\nWe\u2019ll say, good-by to orange groves,\nTo shady nooks and lovers\u2019 coves,\nTo balmy air, and joyous time,\nFound in this wondrous southern clime.\nAnd, when we can no more delay,\nWhen Fate shall call us North away,\nWe\u2019ll say with love words can not tell,\n\u201cFarewell, sweet Florida, farewell.\u201d\nAnd, if on earth, we never meet,\nGod grant that all in heaven greet,\nAnd there clasp hands to part no more\nUpon the golden glory shore.\nBRIFFLETS.\n120 acres of good land all under culti\nvation, with good buildings, for sale\ncheap. Enquire of B. C. Deane. War\nren House.\nMrs. P. Wright and Mrs. John Cor\nbin have been calling on North Free\ndom friends.\nMrs. I. Fuhrman has returned from\nMilwaukee where she attended the\nfuneral of the daughter of her brother,\nM. Kreiger. The child was\nabout seven years old and\nsuffered for six weeks with pains\nin the head but no relief could be found\nalthough the best medical skill was\nsecured. Similar cases have been re\nrecorded before. The daughter was\nable to talk until the very last.\nPale, Sickly Girls\nHAVE ANAEMIA.\nYour mirror will tell you if you are\nanaemic, for the unnatural pallor of the gums\nand inside of the lips and eyelids indie cite thin,\nwatery blood.\nYou may also have indigestion, J,zzv,\nfainting spells, severe headaches, and feel\nings of irritability and extreme lassitude. The\nblood is lacking in the very elements that are\ncontained in condensed and easily assimilated\nform in\nDr. A. W. Chase\u2019s\nNerve Pills\nThis great restorative sharpens the appetite,\ninvigorates the nerves which control the diges\ntive fluids, strengthens the heart\u2019s action and\ngradually and naturally restores the sufferer\nfrom weak blood to health, strength and vigor.\nSee that portrait and signature of A. W. Chase\nM. D., the famous Receipt Book author, are\non the box you buy. 50 cts. at all dealers or\nDr. A. W. Chase Medicine Cos., Buffalo, N.Y\nMiss Elsie Falser, 47 Main Street,\nOneonta, N. Y., states:\n\u201cLast summer I was all ran down in health\nno appetite, poor digestion, could not sleep,\nfelt tired and languid, was pale and weak,\nDoctors could not help me but Dr. A. W.\nChase\u2019s Nerve Pills thoroughly cured me and\nrestored strength and color.\"\nEVEKSON\u2019S PHARMACY.\nMatt J. ftAQQ\nJohnson\u2019s OvOO\nFor RHEUMATISM\nbackache, kidney trouble or catarrh.\nThousands have been cured and I know\nit will cure you. lam so sure of it that\nI make\nAN ABSOLUTE GUARANTEE\nto refund your money if you are not bet\nter after taking half the first bottle. This\nis fair\u2014l am sure that it will cure and\nam willing to let you try it for nothing.\nPrepared at the laboratory of Matt J.\nJohnson Cos. St. Paul, Minn.\n.j Guaranteed under the Food and Drugs\nAct, June 30, 1906. No. 2029\nfor Sale and Guaranteed bv\nJ. B. DONAVON CO\u2019S\nPHARMACY\nAROUND THE COUNTY\nNEWS PARAGRAPHS FROM DIF\nFERENT POINTS IN THIS\nVICINITY.\nWHAT IS GOING ON ABOUT US\nJtray Bits of Information Gleaned\nFrom Papers Published in\nThis Section.\nBut four members remain of the ten\nfamilies which settled in what is\nknown as Irish Valley. These are\nWm. Howlette, Spriug Green, Mr.and\nMrs. Richard Power, Wausau, and\nMrs. John Buckley, Prairie du Sac.\nMrs. Sarah Fancher of Prairie du\nSac, has left her husband, J. W. Fan\ncher, and gone to live with her daugh\nter in North Freedom.\nContractor J. P. Keller of Prairie du\nSac, sustained a painful accident late\nly. A piece of moulding from a ma\nchine struck his left hand, penetrating\nthe flesh an inch between the thumb\nand first finger.\nTramps are becoming a legionary\nnusiance in Kilbourn.\nThe Kilbourn freight depot was\nburglarized of a Sunday night lately.\nNo clew.\nPrin. C. W. Smith of Kilbourn, has\nbeen elected vice president of the\nSouthern Wisconsin Teachers\u2019 associ\nciation.\nArthur Du\u00dfois of Winfield died of\ndyptheria Wednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Paul Karll of Reeds\nburg, celebrated their silver wedding\nSunday, March 15. A banquet, ad\ndresses, congratulations, games and\nother social enjoyments, together with\nmusic by Von Wald\u2019s orchestra of\nBaraboo were the pleasant features of\nthe day\u2019s pleasure. The evening be\nfore Thiemann<s Maennerchor serenad\ned Mr. and Mrs. Karll.\nSaloon Quits.\nThe residents from Merrimack report\nthat the saloon in the town of Merri\nmack has closed on account of poor\nbusiness. The license has not yet ex\npired. The place was located just out\nside of the village limits and was oper\nated by Pearl Thompson. The residents\nthere report the amber fluid was sup\nplied by the Ruhland company of Bar\naboo.\nRelief In Six Hours.\nDistressing Kidney and Bladder Di\nsease relieved in six hours by Dr. E\nDetchon\u2019s Kidney Remedy. It is\ngreat surprise on account of its exceed\ning promptness in relieving pain in\nbladder, kidneys and back, in male or\nemale. Relieves retention of water al\nmost immediately. If you want quick\nrelief and cure this is the remedy. Sold\nby Fisher Bros., druggists.\nBRIEFLETS.\n(From Wednesday* Daily.)\nD. J. Farnum and daughter, Miss\nEtta, of Merrimack were in Baraboo\ntoday. Mr. Farnum is one of the oldest\nliving residents of the county and for\nmerly resided at the foot of the bluff in\nthe town of Merrimack.\nE. L. Powell of North Freedom, Re\npublican candidate for register of deeds\nwas in Baraboo today. He is a wide\nawake citizen and will no doubt make\na splendid race.\nG. B. Stoddard left last Thursday\nfor Walla Walla, W\u2019ash., where he\nwill enter Dr. G. G. Schneller\u2019s opti\ncal office. Dr. Schneller formerly re\nsided at Prairie du Sac and has a large\npractice. Mr. Stoddard expects to be\nlet into the secret of the work and re\nmain in the west for some time.\nJames H. Mast:a of Reedsburg, Re\npublican candidate for register of\ndeeds, is in the city renewing acquaint\nances and looking over the field. He\nreports a bright outlook for his can\ndidacy.","height":"31095","width":"21495"}}
